<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="105" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="38.[227,372,817,843]" box="[227,372,817,843]" pageId="38" pageNumber="105">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,372,817,843]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="38" pageNumber="105" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,372,817,843]" pageId="38" pageNumber="105">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[227,1437,866,1079]" pageId="38" pageNumber="105">
Specimen MB.C.30488 is a fragmented conch with a diameter of almost 
<quantity box="[1085,1171,866,893]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="105" unit="mm" value="70.0">70 mm</quantity>
, it consists of a part of the body chamber, the phragmocone of the last whorl and a small piece of the second last whorl (the best-preserved piece is illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[653,738,941,967]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="38.[227,270,1864,1890]" captionTargetBox="[514,1155,1448,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-249@38.[503,1160,1444,1821]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Fig. 31. Lispoceras sp. 2, specimen MB.C.30488 (Wendt and Kaufmann 1995 Coll.) from Azzel Matti; lateral view and whorl profile. Scale bar units =1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885272" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885272/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="105">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). The conch is discoidal and subevolute (ww/dm=0.46; uw/ dm =0.41) with a depressed rectangular whorl profile. The flanks are almost parallel and separated from the flattened venter by a rounded but distinct ventrolateral shoulder. Any overlap of the whorls is not visible. The suture line shows a broadly rounded external lobe and a rounded lateral lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
